## 2. Environmental and Physical Threats

### 2.1 Extreme Weather Events and Natural Disasters

Climate change increases the frequency and intensity of extreme weather events such as hurricanes, floods, droughts, heatwaves, and wildfires. These events cause direct physical damage to infrastructure, disrupt livelihoods, and lead to loss of life.

- In 2020, global losses from natural disasters reached approximately US$210 billion, with insured losses of US$82 billion, marking one of the costliest years for the insurance industry ([Swiss Re Institute, 2021](https://www.swissre.com/institute/research/sigma-research/sigma-2021-01.html)).

- Extreme heat events are projected to expose about 74% of the global population to lethal heat conditions for at least 20 days per year in future high-emission scenarios ([Mora et al., 2017](https://www.nature.com/articles/nclimate3322)).

### 2.2 Sea-Level Rise and Coastal Threats

Melting ice sheets and glaciers contribute to rising sea levels, threatening coastal cities and low-lying nations.

- A complete melting of Earth's ice could raise sea levels by approximately 70 meters, potentially submerging entire countries and displacing hundreds of millions ([Friend, 2015](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/international-relations/climate-change-is-the-biggest-threat-to-humankind.php)).

- Major economic hubs such as Guangzhou, Dongguan, Tokyo, Jakarta, and New York face significant risks from sea-level rise, threatening global supply chains and financial systems ([Morris, 2021](https://www.vashonbeachcomber.com/news/threat-multiplier-how-climate-change-coronavirus-and-weather-are-scorching-wa/)).

### 2.3 Ocean Acidification and Ecosystem Disruption

Increased COâ‚‚ absorption by oceans leads to acidification, harming marine life, especially shellfish and coral reefs, which are vital for biodiversity and fisheries.

- Ocean acidity has increased by about 30% since the industrial revolution, with unknown but potentially severe consequences for marine ecosystems ([Friend, 2015](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/international-relations/climate-change-is-the-biggest-threat-to-humankind.php)).

