## 3. Socioeconomic and Human Security Threats

### 3.1 Food and Water Security

Climate change negatively impacts agricultural productivity through altered rainfall patterns, droughts, and floods.

- The UN has projected that food prices could rise by up to 84% by 2050 due to declining yields ([Morris, 2021](https://www.vashonbeachcomber.com/news/threat-multiplier-how-climate-change-coronavirus-and-weather-are-scorching-wa/)).

- Water scarcity is increasing in many regions, with 30-50% of mining production occurring in areas already experiencing high water stress, threatening economic activities and community livelihoods ([Morris, 2021](https://www.vashonbeachcomber.com/news/threat-multiplier-how-climate-change-coronavirus-and-weather-are-scorching-wa/)).

### 3.2 Migration and Displacement

Environmental degradation and extreme weather events force millions to migrate, often internally but increasingly across borders.

- Climate change may cause over 143 million people in Sub-Saharan Africa, South Asia, and Latin America to move within their countries by 2050 ([White House, 2021](https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Climate-Change-and-Migration-Report.pdf)).

- Displacement leads to social tensions in host communities and strains on infrastructure and services, potentially destabilizing regions.

### 3.3 Conflict and Political Instability

Climate change-related stresses can exacerbate existing conflicts or contribute to new ones by intensifying competition over scarce resources.

- Studies indicate that for each standard deviation increase in temperature or extreme rainfall, interpersonal violence rises by 4% and intergroup conflict by 14% ([Burke et al., 2015](https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/10.1146/annurev-economics-080614-115430)).

- Examples include the Syrian civil war, where drought-induced displacement was a contributing factor, and conflicts in the Sahel region linked to resource scarcity ([Barnett & Adger, 2007](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.polgeo.2007.03.003)).

