## 4. Economic and Industry Impacts

### 4.1 Disruption of Supply Chains and Industries

Climate change affects industries through direct damage to assets and indirect impacts on supply chains.

| Industry              | Climate Impact                                            | Economic Consequence                                  |
|-----------------------|----------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------|
| Mining                | Water shortages, protests, operational disruptions       | Loss of $150 billion in annual revenues (2017 data)  |
| Manufacturing         | Vulnerability to sea-level rise and extreme weather      | Threats to hubs generating 20% of China's GDP         |
| Commercial Fishing    | Habitat loss, ocean acidification                         | Multi-billion-dollar industry losses                   |
| Energy                | Infrastructure damage, resource scarcity                  | Increased costs and supply instability                 |
| Insurance             | Increased claims from disasters                           | $82 billion insured losses in 2020                     |

### 4.2 Insurance Industry Challenges

The insurance sector faces rising claims and risks, with some risks becoming uninsurable.

- Natural disaster losses in 2020 were the fifth-highest since 1970, stressing insurers and consumers ([Swiss Re Institute, 2021](https://www.swissre.com/institute/research/sigma-research/sigma-2021-01.html)).

---

## 5. Health and Psychological Impacts

- Climate change contributes to increased mortality from heatwaves and the spread of diseases ([Mora et al., 2017](https://www.nature.com/articles/nclimate3322)).

- Psychological stress arises from direct trauma, uncertainty, and social disruptions, potentially increasing violence and social unrest ([Doherty & Clayton, 2011](https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2011-11482-001)).

---

## 6. Security and Geopolitical Implications

### 6.1 National and International Security

- The U.S. Department of Defense and NATO recognize climate change as a significant security threat that exacerbates instability and resource conflicts ([Morris, 2021](https://www.vashonbeachcomber.com/news/threat-multiplier-how-climate-change-coronavirus-and-weather-are-scorching-wa/)).

- Climate change threatens territorial integrity (e.g., small island states) and may challenge national identities through migration and resource disputes ([Climate Security - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate_security)).

### 6.2 Conflict Risk Amplification

- Climate change acts as a risk multiplier, increasing the likelihood of low-intensity conflicts, terrorism recruitment, and social unrest in vulnerable regions ([Morris, 2021](https://www.vashonbeachcomber.com/news/threat-multiplier-how-climate-change-coronavirus-and-weather-are-scorching-wa/)).

